p:
A growing body of literature offers evaluations of how people reward luck vs effort (
 Cappelen et al., 2013; see 
 Cappelen et al., 2017). However, in contrast to these literature findings, our results provide information about the workers' behavior and expectations, not the employers or impartial observers. Additionally, a few papers investigate the effect of noise on effort under various incentive systems (see 
 Sloof and van Praag, 2010; 
 Eriksen et al., 2011; 
 Delfgaauw et al., 2013; 
 Rubin and Sheremeta, 2015; 
 Corgnet and Hernán-González, 2018). However, no research group has investigated effort provisions in environments where effort is completely unrelated to earnings and purely determined by luck.
